```json
{
  "firstValueMoment": "The first real chart renders in the sandbox on sample data, under a minute from sign-up.",
  "frictionScore": 18,
  "frictionRationale": "Low-friction band (16-33): sign-up and a one-click sample connection deliver a working chart in under a minute, with no gate the user cannot clear alone.",
  "recurrenceSignal": "absent",
  "durableValue": "Retention: The fast first chart is a demo, not a reason to return. Sample data proves the tool works but answers no question the user actually has about their business, so there is no artifact or habit that would pull them back after the first session. The trial clock runs while the user waits on a data admin they do not control and a sales conversation they cannot schedule themselves. The flow delivers a single impressive hit, then asks the user to wait, which is not a retention mechanism. Expansion: The production handoff and the sales gate are real expansion paths, but the flow does not give the user who got value in step 2 any way to act on it. The person who can connect production data is usually not the person who signed up, and the sales call is required for the features that would make the sandbox chart useful to a team (more seats, SSO, higher limits). The first value moment and the expansion path sit in different buyer roles, so activation does not feed expansion here.",
  "topDropOff": "The production warehouse connection step, where the individual user who experienced value hits a credential gate they cannot clear and must hand off to a data admin who did not sign up and has not seen the product work yet.",
  "scopeNote": "This read covers sign-up through the two stated value moments: the sample chart and the production connection gate. The input describes the full self-serve path and the point where it converts to sales-assisted, so the friction and value reads reflect the complete arrival-to-value distance for both the demo moment and the real rollout.",
  "experiments": [
    {
      "hypothesis": "Let the user connect their own production data through a scoped OAuth flow that grants read-only access to a single schema or table, no admin required, and measure whether more trial users reach a first chart on their own data.",
      "rationale": "The current handoff stops the person who got value from acting on it. If you can make production connection self-serve for even a subset of users (those on warehouses that support delegated OAuth, or those willing to start with a limited scope), you collapse the wait and the role handoff, so the user who experienced the sample chart can immediately rebuild it on data they care about. That turns the demo into a durable artifact and gives the trial a second value moment that the original user controls. This is a value-moment experiment: it gets more users to real value (a chart on their own data) faster by removing the admin gate.",
      "lever": "value-moment"
    },
    {
      "hypothesis": "After the sample chart renders, prompt the user to save it to a shared link and send it to one teammate with a message like 'I built this in under a minute, try it yourself,' and measure whether recipients who click through and build their own sample chart are more likely to convert the trial to a paid plan.",
      "rationale": "The flow delivers individual value but has no built-in spread mechanism, so activation stops with one impressed user who then waits on parties that are not activated. A share prompt right after the first chart lands turns the value moment into a recruitment surface: the artifact (a real chart the recipient can verify or remix) makes the case for the product to the people who will be involved in the expansion decision (data admin, procurement, other users). If the share drives a second user to their own sample chart, you have a faster path to the multi-user state the product needs to retain and expand, and you move activation out of the single-user dead end. This is a durable-value experiment: it builds a return path and a team-level habit by spreading the first value moment to the roles that gate production connection and sales conversion.",
      "lever": "durable-value"
    },
    {
      "hypothesis": "When the production connection enters the pending state, give the waiting user a second onboarding task they can complete alone: build a second chart type (cohort, funnel, retention) on the sample data, and show how that chart would answer a specific question about their business once real data is connected.",
      "rationale": "The current flow leaves the activated user idle during the admin handoff, which is a retention gap. If you give them a second value moment they can reach without waiting (a new chart type that demonstrates a different use case), you keep them engaged through the production wait and deepen the case for why connecting real data is worth the admin ask. The second chart also seeds a return habit: if the user learns two ways to use the tool during trial, they are more likely to come back after rollout to build the second chart on production data. This is a durable-value experiment: it fills the wait with a value-compounding action and sets up a multi-use-case return path.",
      "lever": "durable-value"
    }
  ]
}
```
